<emphasis id="5C81EADB132AFF997D4A77DA65E0FB05" box="[266,439,1196,1221]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="407">Acantoluzarida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="A9F54D4A132AFF997DAC77DA663AFB05" box="[492,621,1196,1221]" class="Insecta" family="Haglotettigoniidae" genus="Luzaridella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="407" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="5C81EADB132AFF997DAC77DA663AFB05" box="[492,621,1196,1221]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="407">Luzaridella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the other genera not being included in the data matrix. Interestingly, the phylogeny shows 
<taxonomicName id="A9F54D4A132AFF997D2477B9662FFB28" authority="Hebard, 1928" authorityName="Hebard" authorityYear="1928" box="[356,632,1231,1256]" class="Insecta" family="Haglotettigoniidae" genus="Amusodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="407" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="5C81EADB132AFF997D2477B96581FB28" box="[356,470,1231,1256]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="407">Amusodes</emphasis>
Hebard, 
<number id="D83D24EE132AFF997E0077A6662FFB28" box="[576,632,1232,1256]" pageId="9" pageNumber="407" value="1928.0">1928</number>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="A9F54D4A132AFF997EF177A76791FB28" authority="Hebard, 1928" authorityName="Hebard" authorityYear="1928" box="[689,966,1231,1256]" class="Insecta" family="Haglotettigoniidae" genus="Niquirana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="407" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="5C81EADB132AFF997EF177A76773FB28" box="[689,804,1233,1256]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="407">Niquirana</emphasis>
Hebard, 
<number id="D83D24EE132AFF997FCE77A66791FB28" box="[910,966,1232,1256]" pageId="9" pageNumber="407" value="1928.0">1928</number>
</taxonomicName>
as other members of the B-group: this is confirmed here by the study of their male genitalia (see below). 
<taxonomicName id="A9F54D4A132AFF997FDA7782605BFACD" box="[922,1036,1268,1293]" class="Insecta" family="Haglotettigoniidae" genus="Amusodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="407" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="5C81EADB132AFF997FDA7782605BFACD" box="[922,1036,1268,1293]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="407">Amusodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also possesses genitalic glands, a character up to now found mostly in the genera closed to 
<taxonomicName id="A9F54D4A132AFF997F55766F6726FAF0" box="[789,881,1305,1328]" class="Insecta" family="Haglotettigoniidae" genus="Lerneca" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="407" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="5C81EADB132AFF997F55766F6726FAF0" box="[789,881,1305,1328]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="407">Lerneca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
within the C-group (see for example 
<bibRefCitation id="0A644B38132AFF997952766E6483FA94" author="Mews" pageId="9" pageNumber="407" refString="Mews, C. M., Mol, A. P., Sperber, C. F. (2009) Crickets with phallic glands: two new genera and one new species of Brazilian Luzarinae (Grylloidea: Phalangopsidae). Zootaxa, 2292, 34 - 48." type="journal article" year="2009">
Mews 
<emphasis id="5C81EADB132AFF99791D766F61C2FAF0" box="[1373,1429,1303,1328]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="407">et al.</emphasis>
, 
<number id="D83D24EE132AFF997CD7764A6483FA94" box="[151,212,1340,1364]" pageId="9" pageNumber="407" value="2009.0">2009</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). The present topology could then support either parallel evolutions of genitalic glands between the luzarine groups C and B, or an ancestral appearance of the glands, with subsequent gland loss. A more extended phylogeny taking into account more neotropical phalangopsids have now to be performed to test these hypotheses.
</paragraph>
